  "text": "But what determines the similarity of action features, and thus the degree to which actions will compete? Research with non-human primates suggests that actions may be organized into 'motor zones' (e.g., [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , determined in part by the ethological utility of the action (e.g., reaching, grasping, manipulating objects; for review, see [CITATION_3] . The relevance of this putative organization for competition and selection in the human brain has not, to our knowledge, been assessed.",
